66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"253"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/528/tags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/528/relationships/tags"}},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12698"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49310"},{"type":"contributions","id":"53213"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/528/contributions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/528/relationships/contributions"}}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"121536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/121536"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man is being reviewed the day following an elective cholecystectomy for gallstones. His medical history is unremarkable and he does not take any medications. He has a 15-pack-year smoking history. His BMI is 27. Since the procedure, which was uneventful, he has been out of bed and had some breakfast. He is feeling well and has minimal discomfort. On examination, his blood pressure is 126/76 mmHg, pulse 82/min, temperature 37.6\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 20/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 94% on room air. The rest of the examination is normal apart from some reduced air entry and crackles in both lung bases particularly more on the right lung base.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discharge home and out-patient follow-up","Chest physiotherapy and breathing exercises","Arterial blood gas analysis and supplementary oxygen","Chest X-ray and intravenous cefuroxime","CT chest"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has clinical evidence of basal atelectasis, characterised by reduced air entry and basal crepitations in the presence of known risk factors, namely, a history of smoking, being overweight and a recent procedure under general anaesthesia. He can be managed quite satisfactorily with the relatively simple measures of \u003Cstrong\u003Echest physiotherapy and breathing exercises.\u003C/strong\u003E These need to be put in place and the patient reassessed before any further plans are made.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge home and outpatient follow-up: \u003C/strong\u003EThe patient needs some active treatment and monitored for signs of improvement before he is discharged home.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArterial blood gas analysis and supplementary oxygen: \u003C/strong\u003EThere are no signs of distress, no shortness of breath, the patient\u0027s oxygen saturation is also normal and therefore arterial blood gases and supplementary oxygen are not required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray and intravenous cefuroxime: \u003C/strong\u003EA chest X-ray is usually not necessary unless the disease is significant. In the above scenario of mild atelectasis, it is not required. There are no signs and symptoms of pneumonia or any other infection and therefore no antibiotic is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest: \u003C/strong\u003EIt is a useful imaging of choice but atelectasis is usually a clinical diagnosis in a patient with a known risk factor, as in this case, therefore CT scan is not the appropriate step in the management of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atelectasis refers to the improper expansion of lungs. Post-operative atelectasis is a well-known complication occurring after few hours of general anaesthesia.","Risk factors of post-operative atelectasis include: age, smoking, the use of general anaesthesia, duration of surgery, pre-existing lung or neuromuscular disease, prolonged bed rest, poor post-operative pain control"],"references":["Grott K, Chauhan S, Dunlap JD. Atelectasis. [Updated 2022 Oct 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545316/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"103108"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/121536/itemRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/121536/relationships/itemRevision"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"528"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/121536/question","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/121536/relationships/question"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/121536/stemMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/121536/relationships/stemMedia"}},"explanationMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/121536/explanationMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/121536/relationships/explanationMedia"}}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"103108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/103108"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-10-22T07:22:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-10-22T07:23:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"528"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/103108/item","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/103108/relationships/item"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"121536"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/103108/content","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/103108/relationships/content"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\